* R² Score: approximately 0.34

  * The model explains about 34% of the variance in gas prices

---

## Key Insights

* There is a weak relationship between gas prices and:

  * Income
  * Zip code and location within Los Angeles County

* This aligns with exploratory analysis (heatmap), which showed low correlation between these variables and gas prices

---

## Limitations

* Small dataset (131 rows), increasing the risk of overfitting
* Limited feature set does not include major drivers such as:

  * Crude oil prices
  * Supply chain dynamics
  * State and local gas taxes
  * Time-based trends

---

## Future Improvements

To improve model performance, future work should include:

* Incorporating external economic indicators such as oil prices and inflation
* Including regional policy data (taxes and regulations)
* Expanding dataset size beyond Los Angeles County
* using an api to display real-time data


---

## Conclusion

This project demonstrates that income and local demographic factors alone are not strong predictors of gas prices. Instead, gas prices are likely driven by broader macroeconomic and supply-side factors not captured in this dataset.

---

## Tech Stack

* Python
* Pandas
* Scikit-learn
* XGBoost

